          "body": "Verses 23-26 are the psalm's theological summit. *Nevertheless I am continually with You; You have taken hold of my right hand. With Your counsel You will guide me, and afterward receive me to glory.* The *nevertheless* answers the *I was like a beast* of v. 22 — God's grip on the believer is upstream of the believer's grip on God. The four verbs (*with*, *take hold*, *guide*, *receive*) span the whole arc of salvation: present union, present grip, present guidance, future glorification. Then v. 25 voices the affection that envy can no longer touch: *Whom have I in heaven but You? And besides You, I desire nothing on earth.* And v. 26 confesses what the Levite has always confessed: the LORD is my *portion* (*cheleq*). Asaph reaches back to Numbers 18:20 — Levites have no tribal land because *I am your portion*. The prosperity of the wicked is land they will lose; the portion of the believer is God Himself, who cannot be lost."
