          "title": "Nearness is the good",
          "body": "Verse 28 is the resolved version of verse 1. *Surely God is good to Israel* (v. 1) was the inherited creed. *The nearness of God is my good* (v. 28) is the wrung confession. The same word *tov* now means something different — not God's beneficence in the abstract but His proximity in fact. Asaph closes by naming what the wicked do not have: nearness (v. 27 — those *far* from You will perish). The whole psalm has been a relocation — from the watching of the wicked (vv. 2-12) to the watching of God (vv. 23-28). The closing clause is purposive: *that I may tell of all Your works*. The man who almost betrayed the generation of God's children (v. 15) ends as their witness."
